There are few protected areas located within boundaries of the Chihuahuan Desert. The largest are the four biosphere reserves—Barranca de Metztitlán, la Michilía, Mapimí, and Tehuacán-Cuicatlán—and there are smaller protected areas such as Cuatrociénegas (National Commission of Natural Protected Areas, CONANP, 
 www.gob.mx/conanp). The little research that there is on the effect of future climate change on the flora of the Chihuahuan Desert has focused on plants such as the cacti (
 Aragón-Gastélum et al., 2014; 
 Shryock, Esque & Hughes, 2014; 
 Carrillo-Angeles et al., 2016) or on ecosystems such as grasslands that are frequently dominated by 
 Larrea and 
 Prosopis (
 Huenneke et al., 2002; 
 Báez et al., 2013; 
 Bell et al., 2014).
